Inventory Management System 
Issue Identification : -

API perform two Seperate Database Commits
This Breaks Transactional Integrity
Can ead to inconsistent data (like product created but inventory missing)
db.session.add(product) 
db.session.commit() here we have committed
But while adding inventory like 
db.session .add(inventory) inventory creation may fails
So product exists in database but inventory may or may not exists


 2) Reasoning : -

In production systems, operations that depend on each other must be atomic
If one operation fails after another succeeds, the system enters an inconsistent state
This violates ACID properties (Atomicity)
3) 
Solution : -
Used db.session.flush() instead of commit
  to get product ID without breaking transaction
Wrapped logic in try-catch
  to handle runtime/database errors safely
Used single commit()
 ensures atomic operation
Added rollback()
 prevents partial data persistence
4) suggestions : -
Input Validation 
Error handling(try catch)
Providing error codes

correct code solution : - 

 @app.route('/api/products', methods=['POST'])
def create_product():
    data = request.json

    try:
        # Create new product
        product = Product(
            name=data['name'],
            sku=data['sku'],
            price=data['price'],
            warehouse_id=data['warehouse_id']
        )
        db.session.add(product)

        # Flush to generate product.id without committing
        db.session.flush()

        # Create inventory entry
        inventory = Inventory(
            product_id=product.id,
            warehouse_id=data['warehouse_id'],
            quantity=data.get('initial_quantity', 0)
        )
        db.session.add(inventory)

        # Commit both operations together
        db.session.commit()

        return {"message": "Product created", "product_id": product.id}, 201

    except Exception as e:
        # Rollback in case of any failure
        db.session.rollback()
        return {"error": "Failed to create product", "details": str(e)}, 500

